s the first adequate text-book treatments of important innovations such as vector autoregressions, generalized method of moments, the economic and statistical consequences of unit roots, time-varying variances, and nonlinear time series models. In addition, he presents basic tools for analyzing dynamic systems (including linear representations, autocovariance generating functions, spectral analysis, and the Kalman filter) in a way that integrates economic theory with the practical difficulties of analyzing and interpreting real-world data. Time Series Analysis fills an important need for a textbook that integrates economic theory, econometrics, and new results. The book is intended to provide students and researchers with a self-contained survey of time series analysis. It starts from first principles and should be readily accessible to any beginning graduate student, while it is also intended to serve as a reference book for researchers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTime-series analysis. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICSÂ / Investments & Securities / General.2bisacsh  aAbsolute summability.  aAutocovariance.  aBartlett kernel.  aBlock exogeneity.  aCointegrating vector.  aConsumption spending.  aCospectrum.  aDickey-Fuller test.  aEM algorithm.  aExchange rates.  aFilters.  aFundamental innovation.  aGamma distribution.  aGlobal identification.  aGross national product.  aHessian matrix.  aInequality constraints.  aInvertibility.  aJacobian matrix.  aJoint density.  aKhinchine's theorem.  aKronecker product.  aLagrange multiplier.  aLoss function.  aMean-value theorem.  aMixingales.  aMonte Carlo method.  aNewton-Raphson.  aOrder in probability.  aOrthogonal.  aPermanent income.  aQuadrature spectrum.  aRecessions.  aReduced form.  aSample periodogram.  